cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|  Hi Everyone and welcome to today's Precision Club session, in which we'll continue our look at the 
Precision 1@H & 1@S Openings & Responses. 

Last week we covered direct raises, change-of-suit responses and the Forcing No Trump. 

This week we'll be looking at Splinters, Mini-Splinters and Fit-Showing Jump/Shifts. 

If you have not already done so, please have a look at the notes I have prepared on Precision Club bidding. You can find these on: http://ocp.pigpen.org.uk You might want to have these onscreen in the background for reference during the session. The Notes on Major Suit Openings can be found at ^*h http://ocp.pigpen.org.uk/1h.php ^*n 1 Heart ^*x and  ^*h http://ocp.pigpen.org.uk/1s.php ^*n 1 Spade ^*x.

First a brief recap of what we covered last week: In Precision Club the 1@H and 1@S Openings both show 11-15 points and a 5-card or longer holding in the suit bid. If you open 1@H your Spades will ALWAYS be shorter, and if you open 1@S, then your Hearts may be equal length but will not be longer. 

Because the Openings are limited to 15 points, there is much less pressure on Responder to come up with a response unless they have something definite to say.

A hand that would qualify for a minimum 1NT response, for example, will routinely pass in a Precision auction. Direct-suit raises tend to be pre-emptive more than anything else in Precision. 

So trump support and a ruffing value elsewhere is normally more important than point-count alone. Balanced "limit" raises with a solid point-count tend to go via the Forcing No Trump (see below). 

Simple Change-of-suit responses in Precision are treated much as they are are in Standard American (ie: at the 1-level a 1-round force and a 2/1 is generally forcing to 2NT). 

|
