cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|  Simple new suits at the 3-level are also forcing for one round. The 1NT Response to 1@H or 1@S is Forcing for 1 round. It is generally used by hands worth a decent 2-level balanced raise in Opener's Major or better, or hand worth a natural raise to 2NT or better.

Before we start using Asking Bids (or even then when Responder is a passed hand) it can also be used to show a weak hand with a long suit and no tolerance for Opener's Major. The Forcing 1NT response does not initially say anything about Responder's hand, but simply asks partner to clarify their distribution. 

Opener shows a second suit, rebids a 6-card Major, or bids their cheapest 3-card Minor with 5332 Shape. Responder now clarifies their hand-type by passing, bidding No Trumps or supporting Opener's Major at the appropriate level. With the long weak suit variety hand-type they simply bid their suit at the lowest possible level. 

So if you play 2/1, or Standard American, there's not a HUGE amount that will be new to you from last week's session. Any questions thus far? 

