|cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|  As we will see later in the course, many Precision pairs vary this to bid the suit BELOW their singleton (ignoring the trump suit) and now the singleton-suit itself can be used for Blackwood or a Control Asking Bid (Beta). 

This system does just that on the rare occasions when we use splinters. During the period BEFORE you start using Asking Bids, this is a method you may want to employ with 16+ responding hands with GOOD trump support, but once Asking Bids are in use, there is a much much cheaper route you can take to explore for slam. 

So you can happily use splinters to show a shortage in the suit above if you're not using Asking Bids. It can offer considerable savings in terms of bidding space, particularly if partner's Controls are insufficient for slam. 

So 1@S-4@C would show a @DDiamond@D shortage and now 4@D from Opener would be RKCB with stepped responses. 

Space permitting, 4NT would be asking for Kings, but if not available, then 5@D would be asking for Kings.

Obviously you have to work out the stepped responses yourself each time :) Some pairs agree that a splinter is always a singleton and never a void. 

I've never played splinters that way, by preference, but it is entirely a matter for you and your partner to discuss and decide. As I said before, although Splinters work fine with this system, in practice they are used only infrequently. 

The reason for this is that once we start using Asking Bids, we drop the "long weak suit" variety of Forcing No Trump hand. In their place we introduce a simple and cheap way of getting into an Asking Bid Sequence. 

16+ hands that have trump support for Opener's Major tend to go that route rather than using a Splinter, because it means Responder retains control of the auction, and because it's a much more efficient use of bidding space. 

We'll revisit 1@H and 1@S sequences once we've covered the Asking Bids later in the year. 

Let's look at a hand.
