fp|t-title|at|Mini-Splinter  ^kresponses  to  1@h   and  1@s|fp||at|
1@S - 2NT and 1@H - 2@S are special responses that show about 8-9 points, at least 4-card Trump Support, and a shortage in an as yet unspecified suit.

This is like an instant request to make a short-suit trial bid by Responder. With an maximum hand with good Controls, Opener will usually bid game straight off, and if minimum with no interest in proceeding further they can sign off in 3 of their Major. 

If Opener is mid-range or if the location of Responder's shortage makes a difference to whether they want to try playing in game or not, then Opener relays in the next bid up (ie: 1@S - 2NT - 3@C or 1@H - 2@S - 2NT) and now Responder shows their short suit by bidding the suit BELOW it (for consistency with the rest of the system rather than for any definite advantage in these sequences).

So the Mini-splinter is like an immediate request to make a short-suit Trial Bid.

It is a mild invitation to game in Opener's Major if the fit between the hands is good.

Opener will ideally want to hold 3 or more small cards in Responder's short suit, or perhaps a holding such as Axx(x) so that there are no wasted values. 

Responder must bear in mind that the Mini-splinter makes Opener firmly the Captain of the Hand, so if Opener declines the invitation and signs off in 3 of their Major (either with or without asking for the location of the shortage), Responder should accept that decision.

The HCP requirement for mini-splinters is NOT set in concrete and the 8-9 HCP range mentioned is mostly a guideline. 

The idea of mini-splinters is to reach very thin games based solely on the trump fit and shape, even when sound game values may not be present. At this stage I need to explain something You need to imagine the suits in a wheel, so Spades is "below" Clubs as well as being "above" Hearts.
