|cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|  So Fit-showing Jump-shifts and Mini-splinters are BOTH available over 1@H and 1@S Openings as mild invitations to game with about 8-9 points.

Direct-suit jumps to 3 of Opener's Major, therefore, will normally not be in that particular range or will have a hand that is in that range but without a long side-suit (or one that is insufficiently "good"), or without a singleton or void as such (or without good enough trump support).

Hands with a strong invitation to game would normally make a 2/1 response before supporting Opener's Major. 

Hands that are more balanced will tend to use the Forcing No Trump first before supporting Opener's Major at the appropriate level.

So a sequence such as 1@S - 2@D - 2@H - 3@S is STRONGER than 1@S - 3@D and a full-blown invitation, probably 11-12 HCP rather than 8-9 for the fit-showing jump-shift.

This is a significantly STRONGER invitation than 1@H-2NT so Opener should have no hesitation accepting it.

